    "findings": {
      "etl_fragmentation": "meridian app_sessions split this day into 785 screen-derived rows (584 'Code' alone, avg 3.3 frames / ~59s each). Natural-block grouping yields 60 substantial blocks (>=60s). Root cause: vscode_project() (src/etl/session_builder.rs:208) takes the segment AFTER the last ' — ', but Claude Code window titles put the project in the MIDDLE ('Claude Code — meridian — <uuid/caveat>'), so the parser reads a per-frame-changing UUID/caveat as the 'project' and closes the block almost every frame.",
      "capture_signal_layer": "For VS Code / Claude Code blocks, OCR/accessibility_text captures the file-EXPLORER sidebar (file tree), not the Claude Code conversation. The classifier's session_text is therefore filenames + folder names, not work content — forcing reliance on window titles. This is why fine ticket attribution (KAN-139 vs 141 vs 136) is hard even for a human labeler here, and why many blocks are confidence=low.",
      "title_as_decoy": "Block 135 (ChatGPT) has 'Task Classification Dataset' in the recents sidebar but the live conversation was trivial ('Hi / whats your name'). A title-reading classifier would assign KAN-139; correct label is untracked. Strong real-world decoy case.",
      "ticket_entanglement": "KAN-139 (create dataset) and KAN-141 (run deepeval on dataset) are genuinely interleaved in the day's work (SKILL.md, FEEDBACK.json, dev_a_sessions.json, eval runs). Some blocks have irreducible 139/141 ambiguity — scoring should treat these as a near-equivalent pair, not a hard miss.",
      "away_time": "13:14:08–15:10:08 had 0 frames (lunch/away). Correctly produced no session — day-level gap handling is fine; the bug is intra-activity fragmentation, not gap detection."
    },
